                        <provenance type="found" when="1869">Found in 1869 by Brash (1879, 270) <q>lying on a low wall in the pleasure ground at the west side</q> of Salterbridge House (the residence of the Chearnley Family who were proprietors of the estate, which included the church and graveyard at Knockboy). Richard Chearnley indicated to Macalister that it had come from that building (Macalister 1945, 289). The parish church (WA013-034001-) at Knockboy was probably built on the site of an earlier church. There were traces of an ecclesiastical enclosure in the field to the south and within the graveyard (Brash 1868-9, 127; Power 1898, 84), but this is no longer evident. There is also the site of Toberatemple Well (WA013-032001-) c. 250m to the west (Power 1898, 83). The church is an undifferentiated structure (int. dims. 22.2m E-W; 7.55m N-S) surviving complete (H of long walls c. 2.1-2.5m) with quoins and a double bellcote (now damaged) over the west gable. There are pointed doorways towards the west end of the north and south walls, with a stoup inside the south doorway and an aumbry at the east end of the south wall. Two ogee-headed windows, one above the other, are in the west gable, with another in the east wall, and there are two simple lights towards the east end of the long walls. All the embrasures are lintelled internally except the east window which has a flat arch of dressed voussoirs and ingoings. The square base of a font (WA013-034004-) is also located within the church (Power 1898, 83). All of the lintels, except one over the north doorway, have ogham inscriptions (Brash 1868-9, 118-30; Macalister 1945, 286-9), and a seventh ogham stone is standing in the north-west corner of the church. A ninth fragment of an ogham stone was discovered in the fabric of the church by stone mason Tom Pollard during conservation work in 2021. 
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed"> Redmond recorded and sketched the stone in 1885 (1885-6, 418-9) and a description with photograph appeared in Macalister's Studies in Irish Epigraphy in 1907 (213). The stone was reported lost by 1940 when Macalister (1945, 289) revisited Salterbridge. 
                        </provenance>
