            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-top-down"/><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor"><persName><name nymRef="#?"><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">MAQ</supplied><unclear reason="damage">I</unclear>MOGʷEDIAS</name> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQI</w> <name nymRef="#?">MUIBITI</name></persName></supplied>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                 <listApp>
                    <app n="1">
                        <note>The reading supplied is from Macalister who says that <q>the prefixed MAQI is purely conjectural: nothing is left of it but the last two vowel-notches</q> (Macalister 1945, 289).</note>
                    </app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>of Mac-Mo-Guide* son of Mo-Ibaite*</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The Gʷ of MOGʷEDIAS is sometimes transcribed as NG, the later manuscript value for this consonant. It occurs very rarely in the early monumental inscriptions and its original value remains unclear, although McManus (1988, 157-9) has suggested a Primitive Irish value /Gw/.</p>
                <p>Neither of the personal names appear to be attested elsewhere but David Stifter has suggested possible Old Irish Mac-Mo-Guide* 'son-of-my-prayer' and Mo-Ibaite* 'my-drunken-one' (?).</p>
            </div>
